What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 7138590 flights and 27 features:

  • ActualDepTime, the actual departure time of a flight,
  • SchedDepTime, the scheduled departure time of a flight,
  • ActualArrTime, the actual arrival time of a flight,
  • SchedArrTime, the scheduled arrival time of a flight,
  • UniqueCarrier, the unique carrier code,
  • FlightNum, the flight number,
  • TailNum, the tail number of the plane,
  • ActualElapsedTime, the actual elapsed time, in minutes,
  • CRSElapsedTime, the scheduled elasped time, in minutes,
  • AirTime, the air time for the flight, in minutes
  • ArrDelay, the arrival delay, in minutes,
  • DepDelay, the departure delay, in minutes,
  • Origin, the origin airport IATA code,
  • Dest, the destination airport IATA code,
  • Distance, the distance between origin and destination airport, in miles,
  • TaxiIn, taxi in time, in minutes,
  • TaxiOut, taxi out time, in minutes,
  • Cancelled, whether flight was cancelled, 1 = yes, 0 = no,
  • CancellationCode, reason for cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security)
  • Diverted, whether flight was diverted or not, 1 = yes, 0 = no,
  • CarrierDelay, in minutes,
  • WeatherDelay, in minutes,
  • NASDelay, in minutes,
  • SecurityDelay, in minutes,
  • LateAircraftDelay, in minutes,
  • OverallDelay, overall delay, in minutes
  • FlightRoute, unique route identifier.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out the factors that contribute to flight delays, and, conversely early flights, in this dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I will be looking at the distance between airports, Dist, the scheduled duration of a flight, represented by CRSElapsedTime, and the FlightRoute. I will also be looking at the OverallDelay, as well as the contrast between arrival delays and departure delays, ArrDelay and DepDelay.

Before commencing my analysis, I am going to add new categorical variables to the data. is_arr_delayed to represent whether the flight landed late or not, is_dep_delayed for whether the flight departed late or not, is_overall_delayed for whether the flight was overall longer or shorter than was scheduled, is_daytime_arr and is_daytime_dep, for whether the flight is scheduled to arrive/depart during the day or not.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will be exploring several variables, one at a time.

I will first look at the distribution of DepDelay.

The distribution shows a right skew. I will transfom the data using a log scale to see if that yields a lognormal distribution.

I now look at the fraction of actual departures for each hour of day.

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5));
# Extracting hour from actual departure times and expressing as decimal
hourly_departures = flights["ActualDepTime"].dt.hour.value_counts().sort_index()/len(flights[flights["ActualDepTime"].notnull()])
sns.pointplot(x = hourly_departures.index, y = hourly_departures.values);
# Changing x-axis labels from float to int
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: int(x)));
plt.title("Fraction of Actual Departures for Each Hour");
plt.xlabel("Hour of Day");
plt.ylabel("Fraction of Actual Departures");

Most flights depart between 6 AM and 6 PM, before slowly tapering off, with each hour in that range averaging 6% to 7% of all departures. The fewest departures are between midnight and 4 AM, averaging less than 1% of total departures for each hour.

sns.pointplot(x = hourly_arrivals_sched.index, y = hourly_arrivals_sched.values);
# Changing x-axis labels from float to int

plt.title("Fraction of Scheduled Arrivals for Each Hour");
plt.xlabel("Hour of Day");
plt.ylabel("Fraction of Scheduled Arrivals");

This trend has a more jagged profile than the other 3 that I've looked at it. Most arrivals are scheduled for between 10 AM and 8 PM, with the most arrivals scheduled for around 4PM. There are almost no flights scheduled to land betweem 1 AM and 4 AM, and a gentle upward trend begins at 5 AM.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

DepDelay has a heavy right skew. I applied the log transformation, and the result maintained the right skew. Thus, this variable does not have either a normal or lognormal distribution.

Similarly to the above, ArrDelay has a right skew, with the log transformed distribution also having a right skew. The conclusion was this variable does not follow a normal distribution.

OverallDelay showed a normal distribution, without need for any transformations.

Distance has a right skew when linearly scaled. With a log scale, the distribution was almost symmetrical. The conclusion was that the variable follows a lognormal distribution.

ActualElapsedTime is right skewed. When a log scale is applied, the distribution is more symmetrical, although with a smoother slope on the left than on the right. The conclusion was this distribution is approximately lognormal. CRSElapsedTime showed similar distribution after similar transformation.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Much of the tidying necessary was already completed during the wrangling phase, and thus there was no further work in that regard. However, some outliers still remained for some of the variables, and limits had to be applied on the x-axes of many of the histograms, for readability and intrepretability of the plots.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I observed that flights scheduled to depart in the late afternoon to early evening saw more delayed than on time flights.

Flights scheduled to arrive at 6 PM or later also showed more delayed flights, while flights earlier in the day had more on time flights.

Additionally, flight delays tend to happen to similar extents for both longer flights and shorter flights, in terms of duration.

Expectedly, following from the above, the relationship with flight distance is similar for both groups, since more distant flights are likely to have higher durations. The distribution of distance is almost exactly the same for both gorups.
